</i></p><p class="sc-cZMNgc hqfPHB pf-16_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3"><span style="color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">In the intricate web of the global economy, the Bank of England (BoE) stands as a cornerstone institution, pivotal in maintaining financial stability and fostering economic growth. As the central bank of the United Kingdom, its influence permeates various aspects of the nation's financial landscape. In this blog, Dr Richard Dune aims to elucidate the role of the Bank of England, highlighting key functions, statistics, and best practices for compliance with relevant legislation and regulations.</span></p></div></div></div></div></div><button type="button" style="visibility:visible" aria-label="Previous" class="pf-slider-prev none hide"></button><button type="button" style="visibility:visible" aria-label="Next" class="pf-slider-next none hide"></button></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div data-section-id="pf-c127" data-category="Collection Suggestion" data-name="Tea" data-pf-type="Section" class="sc-kYHfwS doYKjf pf-18_ pf-color-scheme-1"><div style="--cw:1170px" class="sc-hAcGzb cVhebe"><div class="sc-egiyK kKHsVi pf-19_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-ilfuhL ejXpQB pf-20_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-21_ pf-heading-1-h3">Key facts and statistics</h3><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-bQtKYq czWvgn pf-23_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-24_ pf-text-1"><strong>Monetary policy </strong>- The BoE sets the base interest rate, influencing borrowing costs and inflation. As of May 2024, the base rate is 4.5%, reflecting efforts to curb inflation.
</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-26_ pf-text-1"><strong>Inflation target </strong>- The BoE aims to maintain inflation at 2%. However, recent economic challenges have seen inflation rates fluctuate, necessitating adaptive monetary policies.
</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-28_ pf-text-1"><strong>Asset purchases</strong> - The BoE has purchased Â£895 billion in government and corporate bonds through quantitative easing to stimulate the economy.
</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-30_ pf-text-1"><strong>Financial stability </strong>- The BoE's Financial Policy Committee (FPC) monitors and addresses systemic risks to the economic system.
</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-32_ pf-text-1"><strong>Regulation </strong>- The Prudential Regulation Authority (PRA), part of the BoE, supervises around 1,500 financial institutions to ensure their safety and soundness.
</li></ul></div></div></div><div class="sc-egiyK kKHsVi pf-34_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-ilfuhL ejXpQB pf-35_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-36_ pf-heading-1-h3">Key definitions
